    "body" : "<p>Yes, you can do it. An interface can extend multiple interfaces, as shown here:</p>\n\n<pre><code>interface Maininterface extends inter1, inter2, inter3 {  \n  // methods\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>A single class can also implement multiple interfaces. What if two interfaces have a method defining the same name and signature?</p>\n\n<p>There is a tricky point:</p>\n\n<pre><code>interface A {\n    void test();\n}\n\ninterface B {\n    void test();\n}\n\nclass C implements A, B {\n\n    @Override\n    public void test() {\n\n    }     \n\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Then single implementation works for both :).</p>\n\n<p>Read my complete post here:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://codeinventions.blogspot.com/2014/07/can-interface-extend-multiple.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://codeinventions.blogspot.com/2014/07/can-interface-extend-multiple.html</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2915411,
      "reputation" : 14416,
      "user_id" : 2498729,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 69,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/8wdJC.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "But I&#39;m Not A Wrapper Class",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2498729/but-im-not-a-wrapper-class"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 92,
    "last_activity_date" : 1382543346,
    "creation_date" : 1382543346,
    "answer_id" : 19546440,
    "question_id" : 19546357,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>An <strong>interface</strong> can <strong>extend multiple interfaces</strong>.  </p>\n\n<p>A <strong>class</strong> can <strong>implement multiple interfaces</strong>.  </p>\n\n<p>However, a <strong>class</strong> can only <strong>extend a single class</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Careful how you use the words <code>extends</code> and <code>implements</code> when talking about <code>interface</code> and <code>class</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1005212,
      "reputation" : 28857,
      "user_id" : 1019167,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 92,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/juW4C.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "AlexWien",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1019167/alexwien"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1382543357,
    "creation_date" : 1382543357,
    "answer_id" : 19546444,
    "question_id" : 19546357,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can extend multiple <code>Interfaces</code> but you cannot extend multiple <code>classes</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The reason that it is not possible in Java to extending multiple classes, is the bad experience from C++ where this is possible.</p>\n\n<p>The alternative for multipe inheritance is that a class can implement multiple interfaces (or an Interface can extend multiple Interfaces)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3287900,
      "reputation" : 364,
      "user_id" : 2766866,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/76890ef4ba60552fae529a0d9387e08a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Cem Sultan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2766866/cem-sultan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1382543436,
    "creation_date" : 1382543436,
    "answer_id" : 19546472,
    "question_id" : 19546357,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I think your confusion lies with multiple inheritance, in which it is bad practise to do so and in Java this is also not possible.  However, implementing multiple interfaces is allowed in Java and it is also safe.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3278604,
      "reputation" : 1746,
      "user_id" : 2759803,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 67,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/289244fb2f15b96bcd9e91b3b482bb64?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "mmdc",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2759803/mmdc"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1382543437,
    "creation_date" : 1382543437,
    "answer_id" : 19546474,
    "question_id" : 19546357,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>A Java class can only extend one parent class. Multiple inheritance is not allowed. Interfaces are not classes, however, and an interface can extend more than one parent interface.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>for example, take a look here: <a href=\"http://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_interfaces.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_interfaces.htm</a></p>\n"
  }, {
